Ex 8

# Set parameters
obs <- 100
sim <- 1000

set.seed(1)

# Generate independent variables with different distributions
generate_data <- function(n) {
  data.frame(
    X1 = runif(n),             # Uniform distribution
    X2 = rnorm(n),              # Normal distribution
    X3 = rbinom(n, 1, 0.5),     # Binary with p = 0.5
    X4 = rbinom(n, 1, 0.1)      # Binary with p = 0.1
  )
}

# Initialize storage for selected split variables
selected_splits <- replicate(sim, {
  data_sample <- generate_data(obs)          # Generate data for each simulation
  target_var <- rnorm(obs)                   # Generate target variable
  tree_model <- rpart(target_var ~ ., data = data_sample, control = rpart.control(maxdepth = 1)) 
  as.character(tree_model$frame$var[1])          # Extract and store the root split variable
})

# Calculate probability of each feature being selected as the split variable
prop.table(table(selected_splits))
## selected_splits
##    X1    X2    X3    X4 
## 0.454 0.469 0.047 0.030

Ex 9

library(rpart)
library(ggplot2)
# Set up simulations
obs <- 100
sims <- 100

mse_linear <- rep(0,sims)
mse_tree <- rep(0,sims)
tree_terminal_nodes <- rep(0,sims)

# Run simulations
for (i in seq_len(sims)) {
  x_vals <- rnorm(obs)
  y_vals <- x_vals + rnorm(obs, sd = sqrt(0.1))
  
  # Fit linear model
  linear_model <- lm(y_vals ~ x_vals)
  pred_linear <- predict(linear_model)
  mse_linear[i] <- mean((y_vals - pred_linear)^2)
  
  # Fit and prune regression tree
  tree_fit <- rpart(y_vals ~ x_vals, control = rpart.control(cp = 0))
  optimal_cp <- tree_fit$cptable[which.min(tree_fit$cptable[,"xerror"]), "CP"]
  pruned_tree <- prune(tree_fit, cp = optimal_cp)
  pred_tree <- predict(pruned_tree)
  
  mse_tree[i] <- mean((y_vals - pred_tree)^2)
  tree_terminal_nodes[i] <- length(unique(pruned_tree$where))
}
# Sample visualization of predictions
x_vals <- rnorm(obs)
y_vals <- x_vals + rnorm(obs, sd = sqrt(0.1))

# Fit models
linear_model <- lm(y_vals ~ x_vals)
pred_linear <- predict(linear_model)

tree_fit <- rpart(y_vals ~ x_vals, control = rpart.control(cp = 0))
optimal_cp <- tree_fit$cptable[which.min(tree_fit$cptable[,"xerror"]), "CP"]
pruned_tree <- prune(tree_fit, cp = optimal_cp)
pred_tree <- predict(pruned_tree)

# Prepare data for plotting
plotting_data <- data.frame(x = x_vals, y = y_vals, lm_prediction = pred_linear, tree_prediction = pred_tree)

# Create plot
ggplot(plotting_data, aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point(color = "darkgray", alpha = 0.9) +
  geom_line(aes(y = lm_prediction), color = "darkgreen", linetype = "solid") +
  geom_line(aes(y = tree_prediction), color = "purple", linetype = "dotted") +
  labs(title = "Linear Model vs. Regression Tree Predictions",
       x = "Predictor (x)", y = "Response (y)") +
  theme_minimal()

mean(mse_linear)
## [1] 0.09957116
mean(mse_tree)
## [1] 0.1143374
mean(tree_terminal_nodes)
## [1] 7.46
mean(mse_linear) < mean(mse_tree)
## [1] TRUE

Ex 10

if (!requireNamespace("ElemStatLearn")) {
    URL <- "https://cran.r-project.org/src/contrib/Archive/ElemStatLearn"
    install.packages(file.path(URL, "ElemStatLearn_2015.6.26.2.tar.gz"))
}
## Loading required namespace: ElemStatLearn
library(rpart)
library(rpart.plot)
data("spam", package = "ElemStatLearn")
set.seed(5)
test_index <- sample(nrow(spam), 1000)
train <- spam[-test_index,]
test <- spam[test_index,]

a)

#Fit glm
glm <- glm(spam ~ ., data = train, family = binomial(link = "logit"))
## Warning: glm.fit: fitted probabilities numerically 0 or 1 occurred

b)

#Fit classification tree
tree <- rpart(
  spam ~ .,
  data = train,
  method = "class",
  cp = 0.0001
)
#Plot cross-validated error rate for different values of cp
plotcp(tree)

#Optimal complexity parameter
opt_cp <- tree$cptable[which.min(tree$cptable[,"xerror"]), "CP"]
#Pruning the tree
tree <- prune(tree, cp = opt_cp)

# Visualise the tree
rpart.plot(tree, type = 2, extra = 101, under = TRUE)

c)

# GLM model predictions
glm_prediction <- predict(glm, newdata = test, type = "response")
glm_prediction <- ifelse(glm_prediction > 0.5, "spam", "email")

# Pruned tree model predictions
tree_prediction <- predict(tree, newdata = test, type = "class")
# Accuracy for GLM model
glm_accuracy <- mean(glm_prediction == test$spam)

# Accuracy for pruned tree model
tree_accuracy <- mean(tree_prediction == test$spam)



c("GLM" = glm_accuracy, "Tree" = tree_accuracy)
##   GLM  Tree 
## 0.917 0.901
# 95% Confidence Interval for GLM accuracy
glm_ci <- prop.test(sum(glm_prediction == test$spam), 
                    length(glm_prediction))$conf.int

# 95% Confidence Interval for pruned tree accuracy
tree_ci <- prop.test(sum(tree_prediction == test$spam), 
                     length(tree_prediction))$conf.int


table <- rbind(glm_ci, tree_ci)
rownames(table) = c("GLM", "Tree")
colnames(table) = c("Minimum", "Maximum")

round(table, digits = 4)
##      Minimum Maximum
## GLM   0.8977  0.9330
## Tree  0.8804  0.9185

d)

# Confusion matrix for GLM model
glm_cm <- table(Predicted = glm_prediction, Actual = test$spam)

print(glm_cm)
##          Actual
## Predicted email spam
##     email   571   48
##     spam     35  346
# Confusion matrix for pruned tree model
tree_cm <- table(Predicted = tree_prediction, Actual = test$spam)

print(tree_cm)
##          Actual
## Predicted email spam
##     email   566   59
##     spam     40  335
# Construct contingency table
comparison_table <- table(glm_prediction, tree_prediction)
print(comparison_table)
##               tree_prediction
## glm_prediction email spam
##          email   571   48
##          spam     54  327
# Perform McNemar's test
mcnemar_test <- mcnemar.test(comparison_table)
print(mcnemar_test)
##

## 
## data:  comparison_table
